      title: 'Transfer functions, pole-zero & step response',
      sub: 'Enter N(s)/D(s); map poles/zeros, integrate the step response, report stability and metrics',
      aim: '<p>To analyse a linear time-invariant system given by its transfer function G(s) = N(s)/D(s): to locate the poles and zeros in the complex s-plane, compute the unit-step response, and extract the stability, natural frequency, damping ratio, percent overshoot and settling time.</p>',
      theory: '<p>A transfer function is the Laplace-domain ratio of output to input, G(s) = N(s)/D(s). The roots of D(s) are the <b>poles</b> and the roots of N(s) are the <b>zeros</b>. A system is asymptotically stable if and only if every pole lies strictly in the open left half-plane (negative real part). A pole on the imaginary axis is marginally stable; any pole in the right half-plane makes the system unstable. For a dominant complex-conjugate pair s = -zeta*wn +/- j*wn*sqrt(1-zeta^2), the natural frequency wn is the pole magnitude and the damping ratio zeta is the cosine of the angle from the negative real axis. These set the percent overshoot and the 2% settling time. Here the poles/zeros are found numerically by the Durand-Kerner method, and the step response is integrated by converting D(s) to controllable-canonical state space and stepping with fourth-order Runge-Kutta.</p>',
      eqs: 'Transfer function:  <span class="k">G(s) = N(s) / D(s)</span>\nPoles: roots of D(s)   Zeros: roots of N(s)\nStability:  all poles have Re(s) less than 0  (left half-plane)\nStandard 2nd order:  G = wn^2 / (s^2 + 2 zeta wn s + wn^2)\nNatural freq:  wn = |pole|,  Damping:  zeta = -Re(pole)/wn\nPercent overshoot:  %OS = 100 exp(-pi zeta / sqrt(1 - zeta^2))\nSettling time (2%):  ts ≈ 4 / (zeta wn)\nDC gain:  G(0) = N(0)/D(0)',
      proc: [
        'Enter the numerator coefficients of N(s), highest power first (e.g. 25).',
        'Enter the denominator coefficients of D(s), highest power first (e.g. 1 4 25 for s^2 + 4s + 25).',
        'Press Compute to find the poles and zeros and integrate the step response.',
        'Read the pole-zero map: crosses are poles, circles are zeros; the right half-plane is shaded.',
        'Check the stability verdict and the natural frequency, damping ratio, %OS and settling time.',
        'Switch the view to compare the pole locations against the shape of the step response.'
      ],
      refs: [
        '<b>Nise, N. S.</b> Control Systems Engineering, 8th ed. Wiley, Ch. 4 (time response) & Ch. 6 (stability).',
        '<b>Ogata, K.</b> Modern Control Engineering, 5th ed. Pearson, Ch. 5 (transient & steady-state response).',
        '<b>Franklin, Powell & Emami-Naeini.</b> Feedback Control of Dynamic Systems, 7th ed. Pearson, Ch. 3.'
      ],
      quiz: [
        { q: 'A continuous-time LTI system is asymptotically stable if and only if all of its poles lie:', opts: ['On the imaginary axis', 'In the right half-plane', 'Strictly in the left half-plane', 'At the origin'], correct: 2, expl: 'Stability requires every pole to have a strictly negative real part (open left half-plane).' },
        { q: 'For G(s) = 25/(s^2 + 4s + 25), the damping ratio zeta is:', opts: ['0.2', '0.4', '0.8', '1.0'], correct: 1, expl: 'wn = sqrt(25) = 5, and 2 zeta wn = 4 -> zeta = 4/(2*5) = 0.4.' },
        { q: 'Increasing the damping ratio zeta (kept below 1) makes the percent overshoot:', opts: ['Increase', 'Decrease', 'Stay constant', 'Become negative'], correct: 1, expl: '%OS = 100 exp(-pi zeta/sqrt(1-zeta^2)) decreases monotonically as zeta rises.' },
        { q: 'The zeros of a transfer function are the roots of:', opts: ['The denominator D(s)', 'The numerator N(s)', 'N(s)+D(s)', 'The characteristic equation'], correct: 1, expl: 'Zeros are values of s that make N(s) = 0; poles make D(s) = 0.' }
      ],
      controls: controls_tf, wire: wire_tf
    },
    {
      title: 'Root locus & closed-loop control',
      sub: 'Sweep gain K over 1+K*C*G=0; pick K, add PID or lead, watch the poles move',
      aim: '<p>To construct the root locus of a feedback system — the path of the closed-loop poles as the loop gain K varies — by directly root-finding the characteristic equation 1 + K*C(s)*G(s) = 0, and to study how a chosen gain, a PID controller or a lead compensator reshapes the closed-loop poles, the step response and the stability.</p>',
      theory: '<p>For a unity-feedback loop with open-loop transfer L(s) = K*C(s)*G(s), the closed-loop poles are the roots of the characteristic equation 1 + L(s) = 0, i.e. D_open(s) + N_open(s) = 0. As K sweeps from 0 to infinity the roots trace continuous branches — the root locus. Branches begin at the open-loop poles (K = 0) and end at the open-loop zeros or at infinity. The locus crossing into the right half-plane marks the gain at which the loop becomes unstable. A PID controller C(s) = (Kd s^2 + Kp s + Ki)/s adds an integrator (eliminating steady-state error) and a zero pair; a lead compensator C(s) = K(s+z)/(s+p) with the zero z closer to the origin than the pole p pulls the locus leftward to improve damping. Here every closed-loop pole at every gain is obtained by Durand-Kerner root-finding of the actual characteristic polynomial — nothing is approximated by asymptote rules.</p>',
      eqs: 'Open loop:  <span class="k">L(s) = K C(s) G(s)</span>\nCharacteristic eqn:  1 + L(s) = 0  ->  D_open(s) + N_open(s) = 0\nClosed loop:  T(s) = L / (1 + L) = N_open / (D_open + N_open)\nPID controller:  C(s) = (Kd s^2 + Kp s + Ki) / s\nLead controller:  C(s) = K (s + z) / (s + p),  z less than p\nStability bound: gain K where a locus branch crosses the jw-axis',
      proc: [
        'Enter the plant numerator and denominator coefficients (highest power first).',
        'Select the controller: proportional, PID, or lead.',
        'Watch the root-locus branches drawn as the gain is swept from 0 to its maximum.',
        'Move the gain K slider; the filled squares mark the closed-loop poles at that K.',
        'Read the closed-loop step response, damping, overshoot and settling time at the chosen K.',
        'For PID or lead, adjust the controller parameters and observe the poles migrate and the response/stability change.'
      ],
      refs: [
        '<b>Nise, N. S.</b> Control Systems Engineering, 8th ed. Wiley, Ch. 8 (root locus) & Ch. 9 (design via root locus).',
        '<b>Ogata, K.</b> Modern Control Engineering, 5th ed. Pearson, Ch. 6 (root-locus analysis & design).',
        '<b>Dorf & Bishop.</b> Modern Control Systems, 13th ed. Pearson, Ch. 7.'
      ],
      quiz: [
        { q: 'The branches of a root locus start (at K = 0) at the:', opts: ['Open-loop zeros', 'Open-loop poles', 'Closed-loop zeros', 'Origin'], correct: 1, expl: 'At K = 0 the closed-loop poles coincide with the open-loop poles; they end at the open-loop zeros or infinity.' },
        { q: 'A system goes unstable when a root-locus branch crosses into the:', opts: ['Left half-plane', 'Origin', 'Right half-plane', 'Imaginary axis from the left'], correct: 2, expl: 'Crossing the jw-axis into the right half-plane gives a pole with positive real part — instability.' },
        { q: 'The main benefit of the integral term in a PID controller is to:', opts: ['Add damping', 'Eliminate steady-state error', 'Increase bandwidth only', 'Reduce the order'], correct: 1, expl: 'Integral action drives the steady-state error to zero by adding a pole at the origin (a type increase).' },
        { q: 'A lead compensator (s+z)/(s+p) typically has:', opts: ['z greater than p', 'z = p', 'z less than p', 'p = 0'], correct: 2, expl: 'In a lead network the zero is closer to the origin than the pole (z less than p), adding phase lead and improving damping.' }
      ],
      controls: controls_rl, wire: wire_rl
    },
    {
      title: 'BJT / MOSFET characteristics & biasing',
      sub: 'Output curve family, DC load line, Q-point and operating-region shading',
      aim: '<p>To plot the output characteristic family of a bipolar transistor (Ic versus Vce for stepped base current Ib) or an n-channel MOSFET (Id versus Vds for stepped gate voltage Vgs) from its large-signal model, overlay the DC load line of a bias circuit, and determine the quiescent operating point (Q-point) and its region.</p>',
      theory: '<p>In the BJT forward-active region the collector current follows Ic = beta*Ib*(1 + Vce/VA), where beta is the current gain and VA is the Early voltage producing the slight upward slope; for Vce below about 0.2 V the device saturates and Ic collapses, while Ib = 0 gives cutoff. For the n-MOSFET the square-law model gives Id = 0.5*k*(Vgs - Vth)^2*(1 + lambda*Vds) in saturation and Id = k[(Vgs - Vth)Vds - Vds^2/2] in triode, with cutoff for Vgs below the threshold Vth. The bias network sets a DC load line Vce = Vcc - Ic*Rc (or Vds = Vdd - Id*Rd): a straight line from (Vcc, 0) to (0, Vcc/Rc). The intersection of the device curve for the operating input with the load line is the Q-point, which must sit in the active/saturation region for linear amplification.</p>',
      eqs: 'BJT active:  <span class="k">Ic = beta Ib (1 + Vce/VA)</span>\nBJT base bias:  Ib = (Vcc - 0.7) / Rb\nMOSFET sat:  Id = 0.5 k (Vgs - Vth)^2 (1 + lambda Vds)\nMOSFET triode:  Id = k[(Vgs - Vth) Vds - Vds^2 / 2]\nLoad line:  Vce = Vcc - Ic Rc   (Id, Vds, Rd for MOSFET)\nQ-point: device curve intersect load line',
      proc: [
        'Choose the BJT or the n-MOSFET device.',
        'Set the model parameters (beta and Early voltage, or k, Vth and lambda).',
        'Set the supply Vcc/Vdd and the collector/drain resistor Rc/Rd to fix the load line.',
        'Set the base resistor Rb (BJT) or the gate bias Vgs (MOSFET) to choose the operating input.',
        'Read the Q-point marked where the operating device curve meets the load line.',
        'Confirm the reported region (cutoff, active/saturation, or saturation/triode) matches its position.'
      ],
      refs: [
        '<b>Sedra & Smith.</b> Microelectronic Circuits, 7th ed. Oxford, Ch. 6 (BJT) & Ch. 5 (MOSFET) — characteristics and biasing.',
        '<b>Razavi, B.</b> Fundamentals of Microelectronics, 2nd ed. Wiley, Ch. 4–6.',
        '<b>Boylestad & Nashelsky.</b> Electronic Devices and Circuit Theory, 11th ed. Pearson, Ch. 4 (DC biasing) & load-line analysis.'
      ],
      quiz: [
        { q: 'In the BJT forward-active region, the collector current is approximately:', opts: ['Ic = Vce/Rc', 'Ic = beta * Ib', 'Ic = Vbe/Rb', 'Ic = 0'], correct: 1, expl: 'In forward-active, Ic = beta*Ib (with a mild Early-effect slope from the 1 + Vce/VA term).' },
        { q: 'A DC load line for a common-emitter stage runs between the points:', opts: ['(0,0) and (Vcc, Vcc/Rc)', '(Vcc, 0) and (0, Vcc/Rc)', '(0, Vcc) and (Vcc, 0) only', '(Vcc, Vcc) and (0,0)'], correct: 1, expl: 'Vce = Vcc - Ic*Rc gives x-intercept (Vcc, 0) and y-intercept (0, Vcc/Rc).' },
        { q: 'An n-MOSFET operates in saturation (active) when:', opts: ['Vgs less than Vth', 'Vds less than Vgs - Vth', 'Vds greater than or equal to Vgs - Vth and Vgs greater than Vth', 'Vds = 0'], correct: 2, expl: 'Saturation needs Vgs above Vth and Vds at least the overdrive Vgs - Vth; below that it is in triode.' },
        { q: 'For undistorted linear amplification, the Q-point of a BJT amplifier should lie in the:', opts: ['Cutoff region', 'Saturation region', 'Active region', 'Breakdown region'], correct: 2, expl: 'Linear small-signal gain requires the device biased in the forward-active region.' }
      ],
      controls: controls_dev, wire: wire_dev
    }
  ];

  // ==================================================================
  // PART 6 — SHELL: render experiment list, sections, quiz
  // ==================================================================
  function buildExpList() {
    var nav = $('expList');
    for (var i = 0; i < EXPS.length; i++) {
      (function (idx) {
        var b = document.createElement('button');
        b.className = 'eee-exp' + (idx === 0 ? ' active' : '');
        b.setAttribute('data-exp', idx);
        b.innerHTML = '<span class="num">' + (idx + 1) + '</span><span class="nm">' + EXPS[idx].title + '</span>';
        b.addEventListener('click', function () { selectExp(idx); });
        nav.appendChild(b);
      })(i);
    }
  }

  function selectExp(idx) {
    currentExp = idx;
    var ex = EXPS[idx];
    var btns = $('expList').querySelectorAll('.eee-exp');
    for (var i = 0; i < btns.length; i++) { btns[i].classList.toggle('active', i === idx); }

    $('exTitle').innerHTML = (idx + 1) + '. <em>' + ex.title + '</em>';
    $('exSub').textContent = ex.sub;
    $('secAim').innerHTML = ex.aim;
    $('secTheory').innerHTML = ex.theory + '<div class="eee-eqbox">' + ex.eqs.replace(/\n/g, '<br>') + '</div>';

    var procEl = $('secProc');
    procEl.innerHTML = '';
    for (i = 0; i < ex.proc.length; i++) { var li = document.createElement('li'); li.textContent = ex.proc[i]; procEl.appendChild(li); }

    var refEl = $('secRef');
    refEl.innerHTML = '';
    for (i = 0; i < ex.refs.length; i++) { var rli = document.createElement('li'); rli.innerHTML = ex.refs[i]; refEl.appendChild(rli); }

    buildQuiz(ex.quiz);

    // build the simulation controls and wire them
    $('simControls').innerHTML = ex.controls();
    // reset stage/readouts before re-wiring
    clearStage();
    $('resTable').innerHTML = '';
    $('bigReadout').innerHTML = '';
    ex.wire();

    // keep current section, but if sim was active re-render happened in wire()
    showSection(currentSec);
  }

  function buildQuiz(quiz) {
    var host = $('secQuiz');
    host.innerHTML = '';
    for (var i = 0; i < quiz.length; i++) {
      (function (qi) {
        var q = quiz[qi];
        var card = document.createElement('div');
        card.className = 'eee-q';
        var html = '<p class="qt">' + (qi + 1) + '. ' + q.q + '</p>';
        for (var o = 0; o < q.opts.length; o++) {
          html += '<label class="eee-opt" data-opt="' + o + '"><input type="radio" name="q' + qi + '" value="' + o + '"><span>' + q.opts[o] + '</span></label>';
        }
        html += '<button class="eee-btn eee-checkbtn" data-check="' + qi + '">Check answer</button>';
        html += '<div class="eee-expl" id="expl_' + qi + '"></div>';
        card.innerHTML = html;
        host.appendChild(card);
        var btn = card.querySelector('[data-check]');
        btn.addEventListener('click', function () {
          var sel = card.querySelector('input[name="q' + qi + '"]:checked');
          var labels = card.querySelectorAll('.eee-opt');
          for (var k = 0; k < labels.length; k++) { labels[k].classList.remove('correct'); labels[k].classList.remove('wrong'); }
          var expl = card.querySelector('#expl_' + qi);
          if (!sel) {
            expl.className = 'eee-expl show bad';
            expl.textContent = 'Select an option first.';
            return;
          }
          var chosen = parseInt(sel.value, 10);
          labels[q.correct].classList.add('correct');
          if (chosen === q.correct) {
            expl.className = 'eee-expl show good';
            expl.textContent = 'Correct. ' + q.expl;
          } else {
            labels[chosen].classList.add('wrong');
            expl.className = 'eee-expl show bad';
            expl.textContent = 'Not quite. ' + q.expl;
          }
        });
      })(i);
    }
  }

  function showSection(sec) {
    currentSec = sec;
    var tabs = $('secTabs').querySelectorAll('.eee-tab');
    for (var i = 0; i < tabs.length; i++) { tabs[i].classList.toggle('active', tabs[i].getAttribute('data-sec') === sec); }
    var secs = document.querySelectorAll('.eee-sec');
    for (i = 0; i < secs.length; i++) { secs[i].classList.toggle('active', secs[i].getAttribute('data-sec') === sec); }
  }

  // ==================================================================
  // PART 7 — INIT
  // ==================================================================
  function init() {
    buildExpList();
    var tabs = $('secTabs').querySelectorAll('.eee-tab');
    for (var i = 0; i < tabs.length; i++) {
      tabs[i].addEventListener('click', function () { showSection(this.getAttribute('data-sec')); });
    }
    selectExp(0);
    showSection('aim');
  }

  if (document.readyState === 'loading') {
    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', init);
  } else {
    init();
  }
})();
</script>

</BaseLayout>
